data.name: IVFFAQAnswer1
data.value: Fertility treatments are generally recommended to women after one year of unprotected sex, after 6 months for women over age 35 and if there are any known problems causing infertility. Not everyone who is infertile will need to go through IVF. If you are unsure make an appointment with your fertility specialist to find out what your options are.

data.name: IVFFAQAnswer10
data.value: There is no limit to the number of IVF cycles one can have. However other factors like finances, emotional wellbeing, physical health will need to be taken into consideration before you decide to try for another. If multiple IVF treatments have not been successful, there may be a need to look into other treatment plans like surrogacy, egg donation or sperm donation.

data.name: IVFFAQAnswer11
data.value: While every person is different, the standard space between IVF cycles is one full menstrual cycle. A fresh IVF cycle should not be done two months in a row without a menstrual cycle in between them. That means waiting about 4 to 6 weeks after the embryo transfer and negative pregnancy test to start another full cycle for most women.

data.name: IVFFAQAnswer12
data.value: If you are having an embryo transfer, you can usually travel the same day. However, take into consideration what medical care is available to you at your place of holiday or work trip, in the event you need urgent medical care.

data.name: IVFFAQAnswer13
data.value: You can colour your hair during the first two weeks of each IVF cycle. From mid-cycle on, it is a smart idea to wait until after 12 weeks to dye your hair.

data.name: IVFFAQAnswer2
data.value: Providing your doctor with a full and accurate history will enhance your chances of success. Bring along with you any recent records you may have regarding previous fertility treatments, prior gynaecological surgery, etc.

data.name: IVFFAQAnswer3
data.value: During the first consultation, you will usually discuss your fertility and family medical history, your goals, and your treatment options with the doctor. He or she will review what you can expect during the course such treatments.

data.name: IVFFAQAnswer4
data.value: Fertility treatments are generally very safe, but all medical procedures carry some risk of potential side effects. Hormonal injections are merely larger dosages of naturally occurring hormones in the body, these higher dosages are what may cause some side effects like bloating.

data.name: IVFFAQAnswer5
data.value: Not necessarily. Statistically, 1 to 4% of women will experience early menopause, and for up to 70% of those women, there will be no medical reason for it.

data.name: IVFFAQAnswer6
data.value: One of the most common reasons as to why an IVF cycle fails is due to the quality of the embryo. Embryos that look beautiful and healthy in a lab may have defects that cause them to die rather than grow. Other possible factors to be considered include the uterine receptivity and the mechanics of the embryo transfer, but the large majority of unsuccessful IVF cycles can be attributed to embryo quality

data.name: IVFFAQAnswer7
data.value: Several recent studies have confirmed that immediate bed rest after the embryo transfer is completely unnecessary. It may seem counter-intuitive, but, in fact, a study published demonstrated better pregnancy rates with immediate resumption of normal activities (including bathroom) compared to bed rest right after the embryo transfer. Do however avoid vigorous activities and excessive heat. Do however avoid vigorous activities and excessive heat.

data.name: IVFFAQAnswer8
data.value: Data suggests that IVF and IVF/ICSI are safe. Health risks to you and your child are significantly increased with any assisted reproduction treatments including multiple gestation, preterm delivery (even in singleton pregnancy), and congenital abnormalities in your child. However, majority of IVF pregnancies proceed uneventfully with the birth of healthy babies.

data.name: IVFFAQAnswer9
data.value: It is completely safe to have sex during ovarian stimulation. Although, there may come a point during your IVF cycle when it becomes uncomfortable to have sex. If that is the case, then refrain from intercourse. Listen to your body. However, if you feel okay, then go for it! While sex during fertility treatment is not unsafe, there are several instances where intercourse and ejaculation are not recommended like when a semen sample is needed.
